It could possibly be much more efficient to use liquid nitrogen (LN2) both inside the bowl and as a source for filling the bubbles.  A potential problems with using dry ice and warm water as the source of gas to create the bubbles are 1) the high amount of water vapor within the bubbles and 2) the high relative temperature of the gas within the bubbles.  A cooler filling gas, LN2 (boiling point -320.4°F; -195.8°C), would probably contract minimally in volume compared to a warmer gas, CO2 (sublimation temperature -109.3°F; -78.5 °C).  Water vapor, produced from the mixture of dry ice and warm water) contracts to 1/1,700 of its original volume as it changes from gas to liquid, as it cools.  Keeping the vapor content inside of the bubble as dry as possible helps to decrease this phase change loss of volume
